<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
bill wrote:
&gt;      The biggest problem with wind is that it's so dramatically
&gt; unreliable, and therefore must be either backed up with gas or oil
&gt; plants or stored in order to be useable....
">

Uno, billy keeps rolling this out as if to create a truth. But by
applying a little critical thinking, it really doesn't fly.

First, he leaves unsaid that the cost of initial plant infrastructure
does in no way reflect the cost from building it to decommission.

Last time I looked it cost $1/watt to build a coal plant but $3-$5/watt
over its lifetime. So in the case of coal, 'backing wind up' runs 25%.
The bonus is conserving a limited resource.

Second, storage. It has been pretty well beat to death that until wind
has a 20% impact storage is not an issue. We have 20gw of pumped storage
in the U.S. today. Why is that? It is because demand is not steady. We
use methane peakers for this reason. It should be interesting to
correlate the times of max wind on a daily basis compared to demand.
Solar at a buck a peak watt too.

Two and a half.
Fossil fuels are not going to get cheaper into the future.

Third, methane peakers. They go in for a capital cost of just 50 cents a
watt. We don't use them instead of coal because of the cost of fuel. So
even in the fossil fuel industry there is something more important than
cost of infrastructure.

I could go on and keep gluing the numbers together but I'll leave that
exercise to billy. If my concern is wrong, I would really like to see
the numbers that back it. All the numbers, not just the ones that suit
an agenda.

Good night and good luck.
</POST>
