Sweden is about 47% hydro, 45% nuclear the test fossil or imports.
So...the Danish wind farms are backup up by Swedish nuclear in large
part. Makes sense.

BTW...coal plants can be ramped up faster than Gas Turbines, ectually,
depending on the size of the GT. Usually a ramp up on any fossil
plants is 4 to 10 megawatts a minute. Firing (adding fuel) is a
function usually of a decrease in steam pack at the turbine throttle
valves.

A 175 MW simple-cycle GT like a GE Frame 7AE gets to 100 MWs in 18
minutes. Not bad.

Here is the rub. The *smaller* the wind farm, the easier it is for on
demand power to make up the fall-off when the wind dies down. The
higher the % of wind unreliable wind power, the harder the fossil (and
hydro/nuclear) plants have to work and, worse, swing up and down on
load to. Its a case of the tail wagging to the dog.

What they do at big wind farms is to collect the DC voltage and let it
out as AC into the grid *lower* than what they make it for...allowing
a 5% or more 'wiggle room' for the system operator to take into
accounts low and high outputs.

I'm not even sure how a true 50% of the grid wind farm would actually
be controlled, it would be very difficult given that the MWs are never
stable, and system operators hate instability, for obvious reasons. I
suppose we'll see it at some point.

